By switching from fossil fuels to nuclear energy (which has zero operating CO2 emissions), we can effectively address the issue of climate change, all while continuing to provide a reliable and consistent energy source that is needed for our current electrical grid.
With proper practices and safety measures, the environmental impacts of nuclear energy can be managed.

3. Uranium mining leaves behind tailings, mildly radioactive rocks from which the uranium was extracted. This radioactive material can be spread by wind, although it is important to note that in some countries (like the U.S.), it is required to cover uranium tailings piles.
2. Nuclear accidents can make surrounding areas contaminated with radiation and uninhabitable for a long time, as shown by the meltdowns in Chernobyl and Fukushima Daiichi.

1. Nuclear waste can remain hazardous for hundreds of thousands of years, and there is no long-term storage solution. Currently, spent nuclear fuel is contained in dry storage casks that are usually at the nuclear power plant site.
Even with the pros of nuclear energy use, there are still some cons worth mentioning:

4. Unlike other renewables, which are variable, nuclear plants do not rely on things like weather conditions, so they are able to effectively provide the grid‚Äôs baseload energy (the minimum electricity that needs to be constantly supplied to the grid).

3. Nuclear plants have the highest capacity factor of about 93%, meaning they run at full power for 93% of the time. By contrast, the highest capacity factor for fossil fuel plants is for natural gas plants, which is only around 57%.

2. Very little fuel is needed to run nuclear power plants. The refueling of a nuclear power plant is only necessary around once a year, with only about one truckload of uranium fuel. As a result, the emissions associated with transportation are also very low.
1. Nuclear energy has zero operating carbon dioxide emissions. The only waste produced is heat (which is cooled by water) and nuclear waste (which is stored in containers).
